00:43:43.710 --> 00:43:45.167
But not all banks are equal.

00:43:45.167 --> 00:43:47.250
And I think generally
speaking they fit into three

00:43:47.250 --> 00:43:48.560
different categories.

00:43:48.560 --> 00:43:50.980
So category one are the
ones who don't really

00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:53.780
understand what it is
or what it could mean.

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:56.010
But they know that
it's a big deal.

00:43:56.010 --> 00:43:58.280
And so they're kind
of afraid of what

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:01.080
it means to their business, and
they're trying to learn more.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:03.510
Increasingly, more
banks fit into category

00:44:03.510 --> 00:44:06.700
tow, which is they're viewing
this as a huge opportunity

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:09.940
namely to cut costs out
of the existing business.

00:44:09.940 --> 00:44:14.030
Because if you're a market
maker in a kind of stock

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:16.720
or a bond whatever it is and
you can assure that settlement

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:18.900
clearing happens
instantly, you don't

00:44:18.900 --> 00:44:22.037
have to pay for clearinghouses
and transfer agents and escrow

00:44:22.037 --> 00:44:24.120
agents and all these
different intermediaries that

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:25.370
add friction to your business.

00:44:25.370 --> 00:44:27.430
So Santander, which
is a big bank,

00:44:27.430 --> 00:44:30.460
said that just from public
equity clearing and settling,

00:44:30.460 --> 00:44:33.477
banks could cut $20
billion of costs.

00:44:33.477 --> 00:44:35.310
And obviously, banks
to a lot more than just

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:37.030
public equity,
clearing, and settling.

00:44:37.030 --> 00:44:40.040
So that's a logical
perspective for a bank to have.

00:44:40.040 --> 00:44:42.300
If you're a bank
today, you're thinking

00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:44.000
global growth is slowing down.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.230
The regulatory cost of
business is increasing,

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:48.660
and there's more competition
from fin-tech companies.

00:44:48.660 --> 00:44:51.660
All of that combined basically
means my revenue's probably not

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:53.080
going to grow very much.

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:55.820
So how do I drive
return on equity?

00:44:55.820 --> 00:44:57.820
How do I drive my share price?

00:44:57.820 --> 00:44:59.847
The only way is to cut costs.

00:44:59.847 --> 00:45:01.680
So if they can cut costs
from their business

00:45:01.680 --> 00:45:04.084
by using this technology,
then they're happy.

00:45:04.084 --> 00:45:05.750
And we're seeing lots
of implementations

00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:07.300
that try and do that.

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:10.910
R3 is a big consortium of 50
banks based out of the US.

00:45:10.910 --> 00:45:13.190
Hyperledger a project
being run by IBM

00:45:13.190 --> 00:45:15.832
that has a dozen or
so banks as signed up.

00:45:15.832 --> 00:45:17.540
There's a company
Digital Asset Holdings,

00:45:17.540 --> 00:45:20.210
which was started by the former
head of JP Morgan's investment

00:45:20.210 --> 00:45:23.280
bank, Blythe Masters,
which is servicing stock

00:45:23.280 --> 00:45:24.760
exchanges and big banks.

00:45:24.760 --> 00:45:27.270
and they're trying to capture
that side of the market.

00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:30.530
However, there is
a third category.

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:33.470
And this is where I think most
banks and incumbents generally,

00:45:33.470 --> 00:45:35.000
whatever industry
you're in, should

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:38.410
be more focused on, which is
to look at it strategically.

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:41.010
Because what good is
cutting $20 billion

00:45:41.010 --> 00:45:46.260
from public equity trading
when the process by which value

00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:48.900
moves and gets
exchanged no longer

00:45:48.900 --> 00:45:50.850
becomes something
that banks do at all?

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:52.170
What if that market disappears?

00:45:52.170 --> 00:45:54.850
You can't have $20 billion from
a market that doesn't exist,

00:45:54.850 --> 00:45:55.690
right?

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:57.600
So to think about
it strategically

00:45:57.600 --> 00:46:01.580
is to say maybe I might
lose out in areas where I've

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:04.255
traditionally acted as this
intermediary, an arbiter,

00:46:04.255 --> 00:46:06.380
but could this technology
create new opportunities?

00:46:06.380 --> 00:46:10.580
So like NASDAQ's move with
this distributed power grid,

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:12.790
I think is a good
example of that.

00:46:12.790 --> 00:46:15.202
Someone's got to go after
2 and 1/2 billion people

00:46:15.202 --> 00:46:17.160
in the world that don't
have access to banking.

00:46:17.160 --> 00:46:19.430
Someone's got to figure out
this remittance rip off.

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:21.055
And right now the
only companies really

00:46:21.055 --> 00:46:23.000
that I think are
focused on big growth

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:26.050
are actually, as you mentioned,
startups-- new companies

00:46:26.050 --> 00:46:28.757
that are trying to solve of
