00:54:53.070 --> 00:54:55.730
and that that makes it a
less scalable technology.

00:54:55.730 --> 00:54:58.841
So how is bitcoin distributed
versus decentralized, and what

00:54:58.841 --> 00:55:00.090
are the implications for that?

00:55:00.090 --> 00:55:01.170
ALEX TAPSCOTT: It's
a great question,

00:55:01.170 --> 00:55:03.336
and it's at the heart of
the governance issue that's

00:55:03.336 --> 00:55:05.750
happening in the bitcoin
world right now, which

00:55:05.750 --> 00:55:10.120
is that there's a fight about
how big the block size should

00:55:10.120 --> 00:55:10.620
be.

00:55:10.620 --> 00:55:12.870
So that basically, the bigger
the block size, the more

00:55:12.870 --> 00:55:14.950
transactions you can put
in it, the more scalable

00:55:14.950 --> 00:55:15.970
the network is.

00:55:15.970 --> 00:55:19.040
But the bigger the block size,
the bigger the computer systems

00:55:19.040 --> 00:55:23.380
you need to manage
the blockchain, which

00:55:23.380 --> 00:55:26.520
means increasingly power will
concentrate into the hands

00:55:26.520 --> 00:55:28.330
of huge mining pools.

00:55:28.330 --> 00:55:32.020
And it is a good question
because I don't view bitcoin

00:55:32.020 --> 00:55:33.850
specifically as
fully distributed

00:55:33.850 --> 00:55:36.910
because most of the compute
power that helps to support

00:55:36.910 --> 00:55:41.340
this network are in the hands
of a dozen or so big mining

00:55:41.340 --> 00:55:46.530
pools that control a lot of
the validation on the network.

00:55:46.530 --> 00:55:49.770
There are all sorts of really
interesting technical solutions

00:55:49.770 --> 00:55:51.660
that are being proposed
and implemented

00:55:51.660 --> 00:55:53.470
that could try and resolve this.

00:55:53.470 --> 00:55:57.680
There's a company in Silicon
Valley called 21, Inc.,

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:00.860
which basically
says if everybody's

00:56:00.860 --> 00:56:04.500
a node on this network, like
your Android cell phone has

00:56:04.500 --> 00:56:06.750
a chip in it that
also acts as a miner,

00:56:06.750 --> 00:56:10.810
then we can help to redistribute
the computing power away

00:56:10.810 --> 00:56:11.920
from these mining pools.

00:56:11.920 --> 00:56:15.250
Others are saying you can have
a routing network in the bitcoin

00:56:15.250 --> 00:56:19.002
network that allows transactions
to only use a few nodes rather

00:56:19.002 --> 00:56:20.210
than having to use every one.

00:56:20.210 --> 00:56:22.043
And that could help
with this issue as well.

00:56:22.043 --> 00:56:25.920
But they are questions that
to this day remain unsolved.

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:29.020
And they go into the
implementation challenge

00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:29.520
bucket.

